  abstract = {Fishing has great importance for coastal development and livelihood in the Caribbean. The region is vulnerable to a diversity of climate change effects of which increasing sea surface temperatures (SST) and increasing storm intensity are the most widespread. Climate change will have significant, ongoing impacts on Caribbean fishes, their habitats, and fishery-dependent communities. This chapter reviews current literature on the implications of climate change on fish target species, coral reefs and aquaculture throughout the Caribbean. The review addresses the following issues: (i) fish production; (ii) observed and projected changes; (iii) impacts on fisheries and aquaculture; and (iv) challenges. Several global models and projections assume that the Caribbean is a data-poor region. Nevertheless, there is some research on the effects of climate change on fisheries and aquaculture. As noticed in several world regions, effects will differ across populations, species and ecosystems, with some impacts being combined and causing unexpected outcomes. For fisheries, the combined impacts (increasing SST, deoxygenation) may result in loss of biomass and biodiversity. For aquaculture, the combined impacts may result in pathogens emerging. Climate change presents challenges for fisheries and aquaculture industry. Knowledge regarding seasonal climate and their influence on target species and better understanding of species tolerances, may improve adaptation responses.},
